description: {"blocks":[{"key":"9f16t","text":"The following protocol describes our workflow for processing wastewater with the goal of detecting the genetic signal of SARS-CoV-2. The steps include pasteurization, virus concentration, RNA extraction, and quantification by RT-qPCR. We include auxiliary steps that provide new users with tools and strategies that will help troubleshoot key steps in the process. This protocol is one of the safest, cheapest, and most reproducible approaches for the detection of SARS-CoV-2 RNA in wastewater. Furthermore, the RNA obtained using this protocol can be sequenced both using a targeted approach sequencing specific regions or the whole genome. The protocol was adopted by the NYC Department of Environmental Protection in August 2020 to support their efforts in monitoring SARS-CoV-2 prevalence in wastewater in all five boroughs of the city. Owing to the pasteurization step, it is safe for use in a BSL1+facility. This step does not reduce the genetic signal of the virus while making the protocol safe for the personnel involved. This protocol could be used to isolate a variety of other clinically relevant viruses from wastewater and serve as a foundation of a wastewater surveillance strategy for monitoring community spread of known and emerging viral pathogens. {"blocks":[{"key":"4gbjl","text":"Pasteurization","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":14}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"c5p2g","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"k2r9","text":"In our protocol, samples are pasteurized the day they are received in the lab to minimize exposure to pathogens. The pasteruized samples are subsequently centrifuged to remove bulk solids, filtered to remove particulates, spiked with BCoV control virus, and placed overnight in PEG/NaCl solution for virion precipitation. Virion concentration, RNA extraction, and RT-qPCR is performed on day two. We recommend performing all activities in a biological safety cabinet to minimize exposure/contamination. SARS-CoV-2 appears to be stable and able to persist in laboratory surfaces and instruments so dedicated cleaning/decontamination procedures are indicated. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":112,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"305j8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6l5ke","text":"The wastewater samples in their original containers (~240 ml) are placed on a dedicated, preheated 60°C water bath. Once the wastewater container is in the water bath one of the samples is briefly opened to introduce a temperature probe and closed immediately. Wastewater samples are pasteurized for 60 minutes after the internal temperature of the wastewater samples has reached 60 °C. In our experience, it took between 30-60 minutes for the samples to reach 60°C.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"51h3u","text":"Prepare a method blank by adding 40 mL of deionized water into a separate, labeled 50 mL conical tube.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1og7i","text":"After pasteurization, remove containers from water bath, wipe away any remaining liquid outside each container and aliquot 40 ml into 50 mL conical tubes. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"8lacp","text":"For standard detection, remove 40 mL of the pasteurized sample and continue with solid separation. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ef48q","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"f6cno","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"4r1a1","text":"Note: The paper that accompanies this protocol includes data that demonstrates the positive effect of pasteurization and of storing the samples in PEG/NaCl at 4 °C for at least 24 hours.
